{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H3, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal attack against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks. Diamonds will provide a stack once the ace is driven out, and the spades are solid — but the count still comes up short without TWO club tricks from dummy's \CA-Q-J-6-4 over your 3-2. The king is missing, and if it is guarded — even three or four deep — one finesse will not do. Plan to lead clubs from your hand TWICE, hooking the jack and then the queen. And mind your entries: your hand must be reachable in between.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The defense takes its heart tricks early — your \HT wins the third round. Now lead a club and finesse dummy's JACK: it holds. Knock out the \DA, win the return, and here is the pretty moment: when you cash dummy's \SQ, OVERTAKE it with your ace — burning a high card to buy the entry — and lead a second club, finessing the QUEEN: it holds too. West began with \CK-9-8-7, four to the king, and never scores it. With the diamonds running and the spades cashed, that is nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] West's club king had four cards of company, so no single finesse and no ace-banging would ever have caught it — but two finesses skated straight past it. The overtaken spade was the price of the second entry to your hand, and it bought a whole trick back in clubs. The repeated finesse lives on transportation; you paid for it exactly once. Nicely played.}
