{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \HJ, top of your \HJ-T sequence — a safe, solid start against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks, and the engine room is diamonds: your \DA-K-J-T missing only the queen. Do not let the near-solid look fool you into banging the ace and king — if the queen is guarded two or three deep, she simply outlasts them. The professional line is a REPEATED finesse: lead low from dummy and insert the TEN; return to dummy — the spade honors are your entries — and run the finesse again with the jack. Then the ace and king can do their work.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \HJ, East overtook with the king and shifted a club to dummy's ace. Diamonds now: low from dummy, and when East plays low, in with the TEN — it holds. Cross to dummy's \SJ, lead the second diamond, and finesse the JACK — it holds as well. Now cash the \DK and \DA, and East's queen, which started with THREE guards, comes tumbling down. Four diamond tricks without a loser, and with dummy's \SA-K-J-2 and the club ace they carry you to nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] East's \DQ-9-4-3 would have laughed at your ace and king — and at any single finesse. Two finesses through her, fed by dummy's spade entries, picked up the whole suit. When you hold A-K-J-T, the ten is not a small card; it is your first finesse. Well played.}
[Note "1:New Minor Forcing"]
