{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H7, fourth-best from your longest suit — the standard choice against the notrump slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Gerber found three aces and you sit in 6NT, needing twelve tricks. Count them: four spades once the suit behaves, the club ace-king with length behind them, two or three hearts after that lead — and the rest MUST come from diamonds, where you hold \DA-Q-J-9 opposite dummy's 8-3. The king is missing, and so are the ten and seven — East can hold K-T-7-2, a fortress against any single finesse. The answer is the deep repeated finesse: insert the NINE on the first round, the jack on the second, and only then unleash the queen and ace.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West's \H7 ran to your eight — a free trick into the A-Q tenace. Unblock the spades and cross to dummy's \SQ-J: on the first diamond from dummy, East plays low, and you win the NINE. Back to dummy with the \CK, second diamond: East ducks again and your JACK holds. Now the \DQ and \DA — East's king and ten both come crashing down. Four diamond tricks, none lost; with four spades, two clubs, and the hearts, twelve tricks are on the table.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Missing K-T-7-2, even ace-queen-jack is not enough firepower for a frontal assault — the NINE had to win a trick, and it could only do that as a finesse, twice fed by dummy's entries. That deep repeat was worth the slam itself: cash-and-hope goes one down here. When the intermediates are strong, finesse them first and save the tops for the kill. Beautifully played.}
[Note "1:Gerber"]
[Note "2:A=3 out of 4"]
